most likely shown in these images?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left atrium","Aortic arch","Brachiocephalic trunk","Left common carotid artery","Aberrant right subclavian artery"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe endoscopic images show the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft common carotid artery\u003C/strong\u003E. This can be confirmed on the volume-rendered 3D reconstruction (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/0788b21e-8b7c-4165-be4b-8dea2085703c.jpg\u0022\u003EImage 3\u003C/a\u003E), which demonstrates the normal branching pattern of the aortic arch. Pulsations and indentations from this artery are commonly seen during endoscopy and are usually of no clinical significance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft atrium\u003C/strong\u003E can compress the oesophagus but is located more distally. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic arch\u003C/strong\u003E is located more inferiorly and would cause a different appearance on endoscopy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrachiocephalic trunk\u003C/strong\u003E branches anterior to the trachea and would not typically be visible on oesophageal endoscopy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eaberrant right subclavian artery\u003C/strong\u003E typically crosses posterior to the oesophagus and can cause dysphagia lusoria, but would show a different orientation on imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe normal aortic arch branches include the brachiocephalic trunk (which divides into right common carotid and right subclavian arteries), left common carotid artery, and left subclavian artery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The left common carotid artery can be visualized during upper endoscopy as it runs adjacent to the upper oesophagus.","Normal aortic arch branches include the brachiocephalic trunk, left common carotid artery, and left subclavian artery.","An aberrant right subclavian artery is a congenital variant that can cause dysphagia lusoria when it crosses posterior to the oesophagus."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70278"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19585"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21618"},{"type":"media","id":"21619"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21620"},{"type":"media","id":"21621"},{"type":"media","id":"21622"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21618"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/kBs2fmk11I9gu6a8p6KOS3udalLkMQ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/kBs2fmk11I9gu6a8p6KOS3udalLkMQ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":410}},{"type":"media","id":"21619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21619"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/i67kbg5oYUwUFvJrHa34CHrMvuYBNY.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/i67kbg5oYUwUFvJrHa34CHrMvuYBNY.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":407}},{"type":"media","id":"21620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21620"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dzw4F4hCEDFKGKzVMie0z2EDH88DXD.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dzw4F4hCEDFKGKzVMie0z2EDH88DXD.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":516,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"21621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21621"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bJI4Ww3K3Kwumzo2DRMg370u91UUe6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bJI4Ww3K3Kwumzo2DRMg370u91UUe6.jpg","isProc